==Properties==

The characteristic polynomial formula_30 of a formula_13 matrix is monic (its leading coefficient is formula_32) and its degree is formula_33 The most important fact about the characteristic polynomial was already mentioned in the motivational paragraph: the eigenvalues of formula_22 are precisely the roots of formula_30 (this also holds for the minimal polynomial of formula_15 but its degree may be less than formula_23). All coefficients of the characteristic polynomial are polynomial expressions in the entries of the matrix. In particular its constant coefficient of formula_38 is formula_39 the coefficient of formula_40 is one, and the coefficient of formula_41 is , where is the trace of formula_1 (The signs given here correspond to the formal definition given in the previous section; for the alternative definition these would instead be formula_43 and respectively.)

For a formula_44 matrix formula_15 the characteristic polynomial is thus given by
formula_46

Using the language of exterior algebra, the characteristic polynomial of an formula_13 matrix formula_22 may be expressed as 
formula_49
where formula_50 is the trace of the formula_51th exterior power of formula_15 which has dimension formula_53 This trace may be computed as the sum of all principal minors of formula_22 of size formula_55 The recursive Faddeev–LeVerrier algorithm computes these coefficients more efficiently.

When the characteristic of the field of the coefficients is formula_56 each such trace may alternatively be computed as a single determinant, that of the formula_57 matrix,
formula_58

The Cayley–Hamilton theorem states that replacing formula_59 by formula_22 in the characteristic polynomial (interpreting the resulting powers as matrix powers, and the constant term formula_61 as formula_61 times the identity matrix) yields the zero matrix. Informally speaking, every matrix satisfies its own characteristic equation. This statement is equivalent to saying that the minimal polynomial of formula_22 divides the characteristic polynomial of formula_1

Two similar matrices have the same characteristic polynomial. The converse however is not true in general: two matrices with the same characteristic polynomial need not be similar.

The matrix formula_22 and its transpose have the same characteristic polynomial. formula_22 is similar to a triangular matrix if and only if its characteristic polynomial can be completely factored into linear factors over formula_67 (the same is true with the minimal polynomial instead of the characteristic polynomial). In this case formula_22 is similar to a matrix in Jordan normal form.

==Characteristic polynomial of a product of two matrices==

If formula_22 and formula_70 are two square formula_13 matrices then characteristic polynomials of formula_72 and formula_73 coincide: 
formula_74

When formula_22 is non-singular this result follows from the fact that formula_72 and formula_73 are similar:
formula_78

For the case where both formula_22 and formula_70 are singular, the desired identity is an equality between polynomials in formula_59 and the coefficients of the matrices. Thus, to prove this equality, it suffices to prove that it is verified on a non-empty open subset (for the usual topology, or, more generally, for the Zariski topology) of the space of all the coefficients. As the non-singular matrices form such an open subset of the space of all matrices, this proves the result.

More generally, if formula_22 is a matrix of order formula_83 and formula_70 is a matrix of order formula_85 then formula_72 is formula_87 and formula_73 is formula_13 matrix, and one has
formula_90

To prove this, one may suppose formula_91 by exchanging, if needed, formula_22 and formula_93 Then, by bordering formula_22 on the bottom by formula_95 rows of zeros, and formula_70 on the right, by, formula_95 columns of zeros, one gets two formula_13 matrices formula_99 and formula_100 such that formula_101 and formula_102 is equal to formula_72 bordered by formula_95 rows and columns of zeros. The result follows from the case of square matrices, by comparing the characteristic polynomials of formula_102 and formula_106

==Characteristic polynomial of &quot;A&quot;&quot;k&quot;==

If formula_3 is an eigenvalue of a square matrix formula_22 with eigenvector formula_109 then formula_110 is an eigenvalue of formula_111 because
